In LaTeX, you can write the law of gravitation using standard mathematical notation. The law of gravitation is often expressed as:

\[ F = G \frac{m_1 m_2}{r^2} \]

Here's how you can include it in your LaTeX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

The law of gravitation is given by:

\begin{equation}
F = G \frac{m_1 m_2}{r^2}
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( F \) is the gravitational force between two objects,
    \item \( G \) is the gravitational constant,
    \item \( m_1 \) and \( m_2 \) are the masses of the two objects,
    \item \( r \) is the distance between the centers of the two objects.
\end{itemize}

\end{document}
```

### Parameters in the Equation:

- \( F \): The gravitational force between two objects. It is a vector quantity and its magnitude is given by the formula.
- \( G \): The gravitational constant, approximately \( 6.674 \times 10^{-11} \, \text{Nm}^2/\text{kg}^2 \).
- \( m_1 \) and \( m_2 \): The masses of the two objects experiencing the gravitational force.
- \( r \): The distance between the centers of masses of the two objects.

This code will display the law of gravitation equation with a brief explanation of each parameter. You can compile this using any LaTeX editor such as Overleaf or TeXShop.
